"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662053","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-05","<p>The Government is carefully considering all aspects of our future relationship with the European Union, including the energy acquis. We want to achieve the best possible outcome for the UK.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2017-01-05T12:20:17.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662053/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662053/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-19","EU Energy Policy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to remain part of the European Union energy union following Brexit.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL4221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662054","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-03","<p>I refer the Noble Lady to the Oral contribution given by my hon. Friend the Minister of State for Immigration during the Westminster Hall debate on the Seasonal Agricultural Workers Scheme; Volume 617, Column 576WH on 30 November.</p><p> </p><p>I would draw your attention in particular to his reference to recently published Office for National Statistics figures that:</p><p> </p><p>“the number of workers from the eight countries of eastern and central Europe that joined the EU in 2004, and from Bulgaria and Romania—the countries most commonly associated with low-skilled labour—are also up year on year. To be precise, there were 129,000 more workers from those countries in the UK in the third quarter of 2016 compared with a year earlier. That does not suggest that there is a major exodus from the United Kingdom although, as I have said, I will continue to monitor the situation carefully.”</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-01-03T12:00:49.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662054/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662054/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of reports of a fall in the number of temporary migrant agricultural workers since the referendum on the UK's membership of the EU, what steps they are taking to encourage migrant workers to apply for seasonal jobs on farms.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL4222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662055","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-03","<p>A total of 1.35 million trees have been planted this Parliament, up to the end of September 2016, creating 1,009 hectares of new woodland. The next update, to the end of December 2016, will be published on 15 February 2017. The Woodland Carbon Fund opened on 10 November 2016 which, alone, could result in the planting of up to 11 million trees. On 8 December 2016 the Forestry Commission published guidance for Countryside Stewardship Woodland Creation Grant 2017, which opens for applications on 3 January 2017. We are also consulting on whether to raise the Environmental Impact Assessment threshold for afforestation projects to help further accelerate tree planting. No estimate has been made of the number of trees felled over the same period or of the number of trees to be felled during the remainder of this Parliament.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-01-03T11:59:35.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662055/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662055/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Trees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 4 April (HL7141) and 19 September (HL1726), what further progress has been made in achieving their commitment of planting 11 million trees by 2020; and what is the estimated number of trees to be felled over the same period.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL4223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662056","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-03","<p>Reducing air pollution is a priority for this Government. UK law sets out legally binding targets to reduce concentrations and emissions of key air pollutants. The Ambient Air Quality Directive was made law in England through the Air Quality Standards Regulations 2010. The National Emission Ceilings Directive 2016 will be transposed into UK legislation by the end of June 2018. Current legal mechanisms for enforcing UK law, such as judicial review, will continue to be available when the UK leaves the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>Air quality has improved significantly in recent decades; we are working at local, national and international levels and will continue to do more. As we prepare to negotiate our exit from the European Union, the Government will continue to ensure that the right policies are in place for a cleaner, healthier environment for everyone.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will set out further actions to improve air quality next year including consulting on a revised National Air Quality Plan for nitrogen dioxide by 24 April. The final plan will be in place by the end of July. We will also publish the UK Government’s air pollution action plan, which will include all pollutants and implement the requirements of the National Emissions Ceilings Directive, no later than March 2019.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-01-03T12:01:17.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662056/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662056/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-19","Air Pollution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what regulatory and legal mechanisms will be available to hold the United Kingdom accountable for failing to meet air quality targets once it has left the European Union.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL4224"
